# Transverse Atlantal Ligament

> The **transverse ligament of the atlas (TAL)** is a strong horizontal band that holds the **dens (odontoid process) of C2** against the anterior arch of the atlas (C1), preventing anterior atlantoaxial subluxation. It is the primary stabilizer of the atlantoaxial joint.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Attachment** — Lateral masses of atlas (C1) on each side
- **Holds in place** — Dens of axis (C2) ([[Cervical Vertebrae]])
- **Part of** — Cruciate ligament complex (TAL + superior + inferior longitudinal bands)
- **Related** — [[Alar Ligament]], apical ligament, atlantoaxial joint, [[Spinal Cord]]

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Jefferson fracture (C1 burst fracture)** — TAL rupture if lateral mass displacement > 7mm (Rule of Spence) → atlantoaxial instability
- **Rheumatoid arthritis** — Pannus formation erodes TAL → atlantoaxial subluxation → cervical myelopathy
- **Down syndrome** — TAL laxity → atlantoaxial instability; requires screening before contact sports
- **Odontoid fracture** — Type II dens fracture associated with TAL injury
- **Open mouth (odontoid) X-ray** — Assesses lateral mass displacement to evaluate TAL integrity

